<br>
Event horizons are, if I remember correctly, the point where the escape velocity required to leave a singularity's gravity is greater than light speed, at which point, no matter in the universe is capable of escaping it.  I think (although AFAIK there is a new model which is being worked through right now which explains things much better) that is the point where the rules of reality, so to speak, completely break down.  There's nothing solid about an event horizon, but from the perspective of an observer, you would watch matter accelerate at an incredible pace (taking into account the increased time it would take light to reach you, might be brighter, I'd have to figure that one out) and then at one point, just..  disappear completely.  That's the event horizon.  If you can see something beyond it, you've not found the event horizon yet. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=aaeyan>Aaeyan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/4/03 12:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1813.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Interesting</span><hr size=1> That movie was scary <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
